  <!-- STORY -->
  <div class="story">

    <div class="story-block reveal">
      <p class="story-label">Nepal</p>
      <h2>I grew up worshipping <em>many gods.</em></h2>
      <p>I was born and raised in Kathmandu, Nepal. Every morning my mom, grandma and I would bow down to statues and chant prayers. Worship was an everyday thing. God felt like someone we had to constantly please with rituals and rules. I loved my culture and my people deeply, but I had no real connection with the faith I was raised in.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-divider"></div>

    <div class="story-block reveal">
      <p class="story-label">Age 8</p>
      <h2>She did not <em>come home.</em></h2>
      <p>My mom was admitted to the hospital. I kept asking my dad, when is she coming back? One day I ran up the stairs and looked into his room. I saw a picture of her surrounded by flowers. I was eight years old and I had to form in my own mind that she was gone. No one told me. After her passing no one spoke her name. So I stayed silent too. And I carried the weight of losing her alone for years.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-divider"></div>

    <div class="story-block reveal">
      <p class="story-label">Age 14</p>
      <h2>The other side<br/><em>of the world.</em></h2>
      <p>My dad remarried and we moved to Arizona. I adjusted to a new country, a new language, a new school, and a new mother figure all at once. At 16 I started working full time while in high school. I became my own parent. I relied entirely on myself. Life felt like one long survival mode.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-divider"></div>

    <div class="story-block reveal">
      <p class="story-label">Age 21</p>
      <h2>My first real prayer<br/>was a <em>desperate one.</em></h2>
      <p>A few years later I went back to Nepal and one night my sister flew off a motorbike and hit her head on the ground. She was placed in the ICU with multiple skull fractures and critical brain injuries. That was the first time I ever prayed to God. I did not know who I was praying to. I just begged him not to take her too.</p>
      <p>One day later she was released from the ICU. Three days later she opened her eyes. A week later she was home. I knew that whoever I had prayed to had answered me.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story-divider"></div>

    <div class="story-block reveal">
      <p class="story-label">Los Angeles</p>
      <h2>My darkest season<br/>became my <em>open door.</em></h2>
      <p>I moved to LA with no job, no car, and one suitcase. That is when I fell into depression. For the first time I could not hide from myself. Everything I had suppressed my whole life came rushing out. Grief for my mom. Trauma from the accident. Pain from letting go of nearly a decade of friendships. My soul just felt so dark.</p>
      <p>That Christmas my boyfriend's mom gave me my very first Bible. It sat on my shelf for three months. I was too intimidated to open it. One day I finally did.</p>
    </div>

  </div>

  <!-- THE MOMENT -->
  <section class="scripture-moment">
    <p class="eyebrow reveal">The Turning Point</p>
    <blockquote class="reveal d1">"You are the light of the world, like a city on a hilltop <em>that cannot be hidden.</em>"</blockquote>
    <cite class="reveal d2">Matthew 5:14</cite>
    <p class="moment-text reveal d2">When I read that verse I immediately started crying. I felt this overwhelming presence of love and light fill my entire body. It felt like the warmest hug I had ever received. In that sacred moment my soul recognized Jesus. That is when he revealed himself to me. I was lost and I was found.</p>
  </section>

